<section class="card">
  <h2>About Potatoes</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Cool-season staple—planted early, finished before sustained fall freeze.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Potatoes tolerate cool conditions and can be planted before last frost.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), potato viability depends on early planting for maximum runway and enough seasonal heat to mature tubers before first fall frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    Unlike frost-tender crops, potatoes benefit from early soil access. The primary risk in short seasons is not spring frost, but insufficient time for longer-maturity varieties to size up before fall freeze.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Plant seed potatoes:</strong> 2–4 weeks before last frost (soil workable)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 70–120 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light (new top growth can be damaged by hard freeze)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Variety length (early vs mid vs late season) determines frost-window fit.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Tolerance & Growth Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum soil temperature:</strong> ~45°F (7°C) for planting</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 55–70°F (13–21°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat stress:</strong> Above ~85°F (29°C) reduces tuber formation</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Potatoes tolerate light frost underground, but emerging shoots can be damaged by hard freezes.
    Early planting increases total seasonal runway, but exposed foliage may need protection if hard frost occurs.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For frost probability context, see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~1,000–1,800 GDD (base 50), depending on variety length</p>

  <p>
    Potatoes are moderately heat-dependent. Early varieties require fewer GDD, while late storage varieties require a longer heat runway.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    To understand how frost windows and heat budgets interact, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Potato maturity ranges widely. Early varieties may mature in <strong>70–90 frost-free days</strong>,
    while late-season types may require up to <strong>120 days</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, choosing early or mid-season varieties is critical to preserving margin before first frost.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (early varieties fit well)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Sometimes, unless selecting short-season types</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Rarely; early planting is usually sufficient</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Foliage can be damaged at 32°F (0°C), though tubers underground are protected unless soil freezes deeply.
    For planning consistency, treat 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary and aim to mature tubers before sustained freeze.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Select early or mid-season varieties in short frost windows</li>
    <li>Plant as soon as soil is workable in spring</li>
    <li>Protect emerging foliage from hard late frosts if needed</li>
    <li>Prioritize full sun to maximize effective heat accumulation</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, potatoes are viable when early planting preserves runway and seasonal heat accumulation supports tuber development before first frost.
    Variety length is the main determinant of risk in short seasons.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can potatoes survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Emerging foliage can be damaged at 32°F (0°C), but tubers underground are usually protected unless soil freezes deeply.
  </p>

  <h3>Why were my potatoes small?</h3>
  <p>
    Most often, the growing season was too short for the selected variety, or seasonal heat accumulation was limited.
  </p>

  <h3>Are potatoes reliable in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes—especially with early varieties planted as soon as soil is workable.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Potatoes benefit from early planting and cool conditions.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 70–120 days, ~1,000–1,800 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>